##### George Orwell
##### Science Fiction, 1949, 328 pages

> Dhaval Bhate, Singapore, 36, sociologist in training says: "Rarely has a novel felt as frighteningly relevant as Nineteen Eighty-Four does today. The chills I experienced while reading it came not only from its brilliance, but from how closely its world echoes lived realities around us. Orwell compels us to remain critical, aware and questioning of power, surveillance and control. At its heart, this novel is a reminder that the ability to think freely, to dissent and to protest is deeply tied to what makes us human."

Stripped of florid language, Orwell's sterile prose reflects the terrifyingly efficient nightmare of his imagined future. Sci-fi readers looking for politically charged, anxiety-inducing parables of surveillance and state control will find this unforgettable.

Thoughtcrime is death. In a society where even a wayward facial expression can get you erased from existence, Winston Smith commits the ultimate sin: he begins a diary. His dangerous quest for truth and a forbidden love affair with a young rebel named Julia plunge him straight into the merciless grasp of the Thought Police.


#### [War and Peace](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/828)
[![](covers/828.jpg)](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/828)
##### Panoramic · Epic · Vital
##### Leo Tolstoy
##### Historical Fiction, 1869, 1225 pages

> Maggie Walker, Devon, 78 says: "As well as war and peace, all of human life is here: the longing, searching, loss, love and heartache, the temptation, the decadence, and redemption, the joy of life and inevitable death. And Natasha lives more vibrantly than anyone in print."

Balancing terrifying battle scenes with glittering ballrooms, this monumental work feels staggeringly massive yet deeply personal. Readers who crave historical magnitude combined with intensely relatable character arcs will be engrossed from the first page.

Napoleon's army is marching on Moscow, and nothing will ever be the same. Thrust into the bloody chaos of the 1812 French invasion, a cast of Russian nobles—from the awkward, searching Pierre to the cynical Prince Andrei—must fight for their lives, their loves, and their souls as the old world burns to the ground.


#### [To Kill a Mockingbird](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/315)
[![](covers/315.jpg)](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/315)
##### Inspirational · Ignorant · Inequality
##### Harper Lee
##### Southern Gothic, 1960, 281 pages

> Gwen Stephens Jones, Llŷn peninsula, Wales, 54, social media marketing manager says: "Atticus Finch is the man that all men and fathers should look to for inspiration. The naivety of the kids provides such a jarring contrast to the hate-fuelled Jim Crow South. Even today (maybe especially today) the book still reads as a condemnation of American racial inequality and ignorance."
>
> Paul Milne, Scotland, 69, retired civil servant says: "Eminently readable, funny as hell, an amazing combination of social history, social justice, fine storytelling, an inspirational protagonist (Atticus Finch) and one of the most engaging voices in literature in the narrator, Scout."

Lee writes with the perfectly captured, innocent voice of a young tomboy to expose the horrifying rot of systemic racism. This timeless classic is perfectly suited for readers who value strong moral compasses, courtroom dramas, and profoundly humane storytelling.

A quiet southern town is about to show its true, terrifying colors. In 1930s Alabama, young Scout Finch watches as her lawyer father, Atticus, takes on the impossible task of defending a Black man falsely accused of raping a white woman. As the trial sparks a dangerous wave of bigotry and mob violence, Scout learns devastating truths about human cruelty—and the quiet heroism required to stand up against it.


#### [The Grapes of Wrath](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/603)
##### Biblical · Exploitative · Migration
##### John Steinbeck
##### Realist Fiction, 1939, 464 pages

> Dylan Moore, Cardiff, 46, English teacher says: "The ultimate road trip. The novel as documentary history, biblical epic and told in language for the common man. The story of the Joad family is the tale of the 1930s dustbowl and a particular American place and time, but its mythic qualities make it the story of humanity too."
>
> Martin Searle, Thailand/Cornwall, retired says: "Painful, gut-wrenching, beautiful, thought-provoking, occasionally oversentimental and always remarkable, this is not an easy book to read. However, everyone should. Its angry message about humankind’s exploitation (and fear/hatred) of our fellow men and women is just as relevant today in our world of economic migration, natural and manmade disasters, refugee movements across continents."

Steinbeck’s prose operates as a thunderous, righteous documentary, elevating the struggles of destitute migrant workers into a grueling modern epic. It is essential, emotionally devastating reading for anyone drawn to fierce critiques of capitalism and stories of absolute human endurance.

The bank took the farm, and the dust took everything else. Forced off their land in Oklahoma during the brutal height of the Great Depression, the Joad family piles into a broken-down truck and heads for the promised land of California. But instead of orange groves and jobs, they find hostile locals, starvation wages, and a ruthless system designed to crush them into the dirt.


#### [Pride and Prejudice](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/1611)
[![](covers/1611.jpg)](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/1611)
##### Porcelain · Steel · Cautionary
##### Jane Austen
##### Comedy of Manners, 1813, 279 pages

> Heather, Los Angeles, research analyst says: "This is a perfect novel that speaks with incredible precision and humour about class and gender. I reread it every 10 years or so – in my teens and 20s it was a fairytale; in my 30s it was a cautionary tale; and now I see it as a horror story (the improbable happy ending is only a thin veneer masking the more likely fate of girls in Lizzie’s and her sisters’ position)."
>
> David, Loanhead, Scotland, 68, retired says: "A porcelain gem with a backbone of steel. A novel which resonates with everyone navigating adulthood and the pressures to find a partner with whom to navigate the world – one way or another."

Brimming with razor-sharp irony and flawless dialogue, Austen delivers a masterclass in character development and social critique. This remains the gold standard for anyone who loves enemies-to-lovers tropes, biting humor, and airtight storytelling.

It is a truth universally acknowledged that a wealthy bachelor is the ultimate prize—unless you are Elizabeth Bennet. When the arrogant, impossibly rich Mr. Darcy snubs her at a local dance, Elizabeth writes him off forever. What follows is a delicious, high-stakes battle of wits as they are continually forced together, fighting off scandalous elopements, interfering relatives, and their own stubborn hearts.


#### [Middlemarch](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/1732)
[![](covers/1732.jpg)](https://books.rob.me.uk/book/1732)
##### Warm · Wise · Witty
##### George Eliot
##### Literary Fiction, 1871, 904 pages

> Katrina Evans, Sydney, GP says: "You can take all your weighty Russian greats so long as I get to keep this classic – warm, wise, witty and just so generous of heart. Critical darlings can sometimes seem cold and distant but this one felt like an old friend. Unerring in its depiction of human folly but forgiving of it too. And it’s really funny. If I believed in God I’d want her to be like George Eliot."
>
> Carrie, Chester, 45 says: "This novel is like an old, comforting blanket. I wrap myself in it every few years. To me, no other novelist has such empathy and understanding of her characters. She never sneers or mocks. Somehow, even the most unlikeable characters, like Casaubon, are shown in their true colours and yet with the most startling sympathy and clarity."

Eliot’s omniscient narrator serves up a masterclass in empathy and social observation, shifting seamlessly between diverse perspectives. Readers seeking a deeply immersive, slow-burn exploration of community dynamics and the quiet tragedies of ordinary lives will find themselves completely captivated.

Ambition collides with reality in a gossipy English town. When visionary young doctor Tertius Lydgate and starry-eyed Dorothea Brooke set out to change the world, they quickly discover their grandest plans are no match for petty local politics, financial ruin, and the suffocating grip of toxic marriages.


#### The Lord of the Rings
##### Mythological · Escapist · Masterpiece
##### J.R.R. Tolkien
##### High Fantasy, 1954, 1178 pages

> Grant Currie, Marlow, Buckinghamshire, 55, corporate communications says: "I don’t think there is much to say here! A masterpiece of storytelling and universe creation. I think I first read it when I was 13 and just could not put it down. I would sit in my bedroom for hours drawn into a different world. For someone growing up on a council estate, it was escapism at its very finest!"
>
> Kathleen Reeves, Somerset, 65 says: "I cannot tell you how many times I read this as a teenager, the dreams it planted in my head, the images, music, history and breadth of where a world could be explored if you left your front door and took a first step. A mythology for our chequered isle dappled in depth, darkness, light, resilience, love and compassion."

Tolkien essentially birthed the modern high fantasy genre with an obsessive, linguistically stunning dedication to world-building. This towering epic is the ultimate reading destination for those who want to be swept away by legendary quests, ancient evils, and the unwavering courage of the smallest heroes.

The fate of the world rests in the smallest of hands. When a quiet, unassuming hobbit named Frodo Baggins inherits a deceptively simple gold ring, he discovers it is the ultimate weapon of the Dark Lord Sauron. Hunted by terrifying wraiths and forced to leave his peaceful shire, Frodo must journey into the very heart of enemy territory to destroy the ring before darkness swallows the earth.
